	<article class="post-151548 post type-post status-publish hentry category-the-great-divide tag-capitalism-theory-and-philosophy tag-downton-abbey-tv-program tag-gone-with-the-wind-movie tag-great-britain tag-high-net-worth-individuals tag-income-inequality des-capitalism-theory-and-philosophy des-high-net-worth-individuals des-income-inequality geo-great-britain ttl-downton-abbey-tv-program ttl-gone-with-the-wind-movie" id="post-151548">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
			<span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/the-great-divide/?module=BlogCategory&version=Blog Post&action=Click&contentCollection=Opinion&pgtype=Blogs&region=Header">The Great Divide</a></span>
		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Sympathy for the Toffs</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Chrystia Freeland			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-01-24T23:15:27+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">January 24, 2014 6:15 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">January 24, 2014 6:15 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="inlineModule"><div class="entry"><div class="thumb"><img alt="The Great Divide" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/opinionator/pogs/greatdivide45.png" width="50" height="50"></div><p class="summary"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/the-great-divide/">The Great Divide</a> is a series about inequality.</p></div></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/01/24/sympathy-for-the-toffs/" data-title="The Great Divide: Sympathy for the Toffs" data-description="Loving âDownton Abbeyâ in the new Gilded Age.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Last year, we turned on the plutocrats. Everyone from Pope Francis to Bill de Blasio denounced them. Even Bill and Hillary Clinton, erstwhile champions of pro-business centrism and donor sleepovers at the White House, decided it was prudent to jump on the populist bandwagon. So why are we still smitten with the toffs of âDownton Abbeyâ?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Certainly, we love âDownton Abbeyâ for the costumes, the sumptuous grounds and perhaps especially for the cultural license an English accent seems to give us to enjoy soap-opera-level melodrama. Plummy vowels apparently have the same legitimizing effect that e-books have had on erotica for women.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Another source of the showâs appeal is the profound similarity between the vast economic, social and political changes that drive the action in âDownton Abbeyâ and our own time.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Then, as now, new technologies were creating vast fortunes, but causing some, like Mrs. Patmore, the cook at Downton, to worry that their jobs will become redundant. Then, as now, income inequality was surging. Then, as now, these changes were shattering social restrictions and liberating individuals from the old constraints of gender, class and even sometimes race, but also made many feel insecure.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yet there is one crucial difference between âDownton Abbeyâ and us. With their lavish lifestyles, the aristocrats of âDownton Abbeyâ may seem like a 20th-century version of our own plutocrats, but they are not. Todayâs superelites are the turbocharged, globalized version of the capitalists whose displacement of the titled Crawleys is one of the key forces shaping the family saga.</p>
<div class="w427"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/26/sunday-review/26DIVIDE/26DIVIDE-blog427.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/26/sunday-review/26DIVIDE/26DIVIDE-blog427.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/26/sunday-review/26DIVIDE/26DIVIDE-blog427.jpg" id="100000002667227" width="427" height="227" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="227"><meta itemprop="width" content="427"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Javier JaÃ©n</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This distinction is what makes âDownton Abbeyâ such visceral fun. The series allows us to glory in the glamorous lifestyle of an upper class, without worrying that we are suffering from Stockholm syndrome. North Americans face many social and economic problems in their daily lives, but oppression by a hereditary, landed class isnât one of them. (That is not entirely the case for the British, which may explain why the series is even more popular on this side of the Atlantic.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âDownton Abbeyâ is todayâs âGone With the Wind.â We enjoy the excesses it depicts partly because we know that the elite cavorting on our screens has had its real-life comeuppance.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Better still, when it comes to class, privilege and wealth, âDownton Abbeyâ lets us have our cake and eat it, too. The show gives us a voyeuristic peek at the pleasures of being an Edwardian aristocrat, but it also allows us to feel smarter and better than the blue bloods of that period. We delight in their fancy table settings â so much so that you can learn how to sew your own Downton-style table runner on the showâs Facebook page and question Lisa Heathcote, the showâs food stylist, on Twitter â Â but we know that their way of life is ending, and that that is pretty much a good thing.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When Tom Branson, the Irish chauffeur, defies class barriers to marry Lady Sybil, we are on the young coupleâs side. When their daughter is called a âcrossbreedâ by her nanny, we are grateful to live in a more enlightened age. Unlike our own plutocrats, the top dogs at Downton are on their way down. Our natural sympathies lie with the upwardly mobile servants and middle-class professionals, like Matthew Crawley and his mother, who will replace them.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But sometimes, when the hard-driving efficiency of the rising middle class clashes with the noblesse oblige of the declining aristocracy, we feel a guilty admiration for the values we know were fading. Lord Grantham canât keep up with the newfangled technologies and more demanding economic pace of the times. Yet the inept peer is not portrayed as a lazy rentier, paying for his fine linens and footmen by exploiting the peasants.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This sweeter-than-sour drawing of Lord Grantham embodies the contradiction of âDownton Abbey.â The show, and the society it depicts, celebrates the pleasures of having money, but is ambivalent about what it takes to make it.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In a series of sharp, elegant novels, Nancy Mitford, herself a lordâs daughter, captured the same moment of economic disruption and cultural confusion. Diamond-bedecked Lady Montdore, married to the former viceroy of India, revels in the joys of âall of this,â of traveling, fur-covered, in a motorcar, while the less privileged cower in the rain. But it is a banking family, the Kroesigs, who are the archvillains, when they are not objects of pity.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âDonât know how you chaps can stand it,â Uncle Matthew, Mitfordâs raging, fox-hunting version of Lord Grantham, says sympathetically to Sir Leicester, a successful City banker. âIt must be the hell of a life, fussing about with other blokesâ money all day, indoors.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In âDownton Abbey,â the ambivalence about this âhell of a lifeâ is the moral uncertainty of an economy and a society in transition. The thrusting middle class that was poised to seize its share of power may not have had the social polish of the aristocrats it was displacing, but from todayâs perspective it was clearly superior â harder working (well, actually, working, which the old lords did not need to do), more efficient, more meritocratic.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But the professionals and the rising industrial barons of that age didnât entirely see themselves that way. Richard Carlisle, the newspaper magnate who knows how to make money and wield political power, wants to marry Mary Crawley and gain the social status such a union would offer. The same logic united Maryâs parents, Lord Grantham and Cora, nee Levinson, who exchanged her familyâs American self-made money for British blue blood. Rising capitalists sought the approval of the elites they would soon replace.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Todayâs plutocrats â at least those in the West â arenât part of any analogous social revolution. The elites they are ousting are their own, slightly less sure-footed, business rivals, and the approval they seek is that of their investors, their shareholders and perhaps their peers. The social constraints the old aristocracy imposed on the first generation of capitalists are long gone.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The paradox is that our era of capitalism is creating a new aristocracy of talent, with all of the perks and few of the traditional values of the lords of âDownton Abbey.â And many of the middle-class great-grandchildren of Downtonâs servants, raised to believe they belonged to a society of equals, are finding themselves living below stairs in a newly divided economy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The economic forces unleashed in the era of âDownton Abbeyâ are recreating the social hierarchies they once destroyed. Thatâs the irony of our time. At the ballot box, we are reacting by electing leaders, ranging from Mr. de Blasio to Mayor Rob Ford of Toronto, who rage against the elite. But thatâs also why, when we get home, we canât stop watching a portrait of an age that was so similar to and yet so different from our own.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Chrystia Freeland is the author of âPlutocrats: The Rise of the New Global Super-Rich and the Fall of Everyone Elseâ and a Liberal member of the Canadian Parliament.</em></p>
<footer class="story-footer">
    <div class="story-meta">
	<p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 01/26/2014, on page <span itemprop="printSection">SR</span><span itemprop="printPage">4</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">NewYork</span> edition with the headline: Sympathy for the Toffs.</p>    </div>
</footer>
	</div>
